In a stationary time series, statistical properties such as mean and variance are constant over time. In a non-stationary series, these properties are dependent on time.

From the above graphs we can see that mean and variance stay quite constant over time. We can check if the data are stationary by performing an ADFuller test.

In [17]:
# stationary test
# adf stationarity test
print("ADFuller Test; Significance: 0.05") #Print the significance level

#Do the ADFuller test for each column
adf = adfuller(mean_temp_train['mean_temp']) #Call adfuller to test
print("The Test Statistic for mean temperature is {}".format(round(adf[0],1))) 
print("The p-value for mean temperature is {}".format(round(adf[1],2))) #Print the adfuller results

ADFuller Test; Significance: 0.05
The Test Statistic for mean temperature is -3.2
The p-value for mean temperature is 0.02

Hence since $P-Value < 0.05$ (Significance Level defined), we reject the Null Hypothesis that the time series contains a unit root. In other words, by rejecting the Null hypothesis, we can conclude that the time series is stationary.

Confidence intervals are drawn as a cone. By default, this is set to a 95% confidence interval, suggesting that correlation values outside of this code are very likely a correlation and not a statistical fluke.

The graph above calculates and plots a partial autocorrelation function for the first 40 lags in the Mean Monthly Temperatures dataset using the plot_pacf() from the statsmodels library.

Next we use auto arima function to search for the best ARIMA models.

The default procedure uses some approximations to speed up the search. These approximations can be avoided with the argument approximation = FALSE. It is possible that the minimum AIC model will not be found due to these approximations, or because of the stepwise procedure. A much larger set of models will be searched if the argument stepwise = FALSE is used. We also use d = 0 and D = 1 since we had no first-differencing but only seasonal-differencing.

The output above shows that the final model fitted was an ARIMA(2,0,4) estimator, where the values of the parameters p, d, and q were two, zero, and four, respectively. The auto_arima functions tests the time series with different combinations of p, d, and q using AIC as the criterion. AIC stands for Akaike Information Criterion, which estimates the relative amount of information lost by a given model. In simple terms, a lower AIC value is preferred. In the above output, the lowest AIC value of 711.106 was obtained for the ARIMA(2, 0, 4) model, and that is used as the final estimator.

In the post-estimation analysis, we would also like to check out the residual plots, including time series, ACFs and etc, to make sure that there is no warning signal. In particular, residuals shall have a zero mean, constant variance, and distributed symmetrically around mean zero. ACF of any lag greater 0 is expected to be statistically insignificant.

The output above shows that the final model fitted was an ARIMA(2,0,5) estimator, where the values of the parameters p, d, and q were two, zero, and five, respectively. The auto_arima functions tests the time series with different combinations of p, d, and q using AIC as the criterion. AIC stands for Akaike Information Criterion, which estimates the relative amount of information lost by a given model. In simple terms, a lower AIC value is preferred. In the above output, the lowest AIC value of 747.494 was obtained for the ARIMA(2, 0, 5) model, and that is used as the final estimator.

Holt-Winters¶

Now we will use another model to forecast temperature. Our goal is to pick the model with the most accurate predictions.

We will forecast the average montly temperature demand for the next year using Holt-Winters model.

For time series analysis, the first step is always to visually inspect the time series. In this regard, the STL() function is quite useful. It decomposes the original time series into trend, seasonal factors, and random error terms.

In [31]:
stl = STL(mean_temp_train, seasonal=7)
res = stl.fit()
fig = res.plot()

From the above we can conclude that the contribution of the trend component to the variation in the original time series is marginal. Moreover, we can see that there is high seasonality in the data.

Exponential smoothing methods consist of flattening time series data. Exponential smoothing averages or exponentially weighted moving averages consist of forecast based on previous periods data with exponentially declining influence on the older observations.

Exponential smoothing methods consist of special case exponential moving with notation ETS (Error, Trend, Seasonality) where each can be none(N), additive (A), additive damped (Ad), Multiplicative (M) or multiplicative damped (Md).

We use the Holt-Winters - ETS(A, A, A) linear method with additive errors, as this is the appropriate for our case. We build the model and fit it into the train set.

Clearly the ETS model predicts mean monthly temperature more accurately than the ARIMA one. It is worth mentioning that for some months the prediction differs only 0.1 or 0.2 degrees celsius, and for June 2019 the prediction is 100% accurate. The average difference between the actual values and the predicted monthly temperatures is only 0.67 degress celsius. This slight difference might be justified due to the global warming effect on Aomori City of Japan, as the actual temperatures were slghtly higher than the predicted ones, especially during late summer months.
